      "id": 1,
      "text": "Old Tappan was incorporated as a borough on October 18, 1894, carved out of Harrington Township.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        20
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Wikipedia"
      ],
      "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Old_Tappan%2C_New_Jersey"
    },
    {
      "id": 2,
      "text": "The borough’s name derives from the Tappan tribe of Native Americans who once inhabited the area.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        23
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Wikipedia"
      ],
      "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Old_Tappan%2C_New_Jersey"
    },
    {
      "id": 3,
      "text": "During the 1894 “Boroughitis” boom, 26 new boroughs sprang up in Bergen County, including Old Tappan.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        21
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Wikipedia"
      ],
      "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Old_Tappan%2C_New_Jersey"
    },
    {
      "id": 4,
      "text": "Lake Tappan and the Hackensack River form the western boundary of Old Tappan, overlooking neighboring River Vale.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        25
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Wikipedia"
      ],
      "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Old_Tappan%2C_New_Jersey"
    },
    {
      "id": 5,
      "text": "Four Haring family homes—Frederick, Gerrit, Teunis, and Haring‑DeWolf—are listed on the National Register of Historic Places in Old Tappan.",
